                    his style is restricted or cramped in any sense?</p>
<p><span class="speaker">William Faulkner</span>No, sir. I don't think so. It may be that his opportunities for
                    experimentation are cramped. I think that&mdash;that any language must
                    continue to be alive. That is, it must continue to change or be susceptible to
                    change, and&mdash;and grammar, punctuation are&mdash;are part of that
                    fluidity. If by experimentation you&mdash;you find out if the old ways were
                    the best or maybe the old ways might be subject to change. I wouldn't say that
                    it restricts your style because style could be a part of the&mdash;the
                    fluidity of&mdash;of the change. Style, if it's a&mdash;like anything
                    else to be alive it must be in motion too. If it becomes fixed, then it's dead.
