                    the same background that the writer writes from. That is, the culture. The
                    culture contains this symbolism which has been established and described by
                    the&mdash;the experts, the psychiatrists and psychologists, and since
                    the&mdash;one man writes from it, another reads from it, it's natural that
                    the symbolism should appear. And since the&mdash;well, in our case now, we
                    both read and write from a culture we call the culture of the Christian culture,
                    and naturally symbols will be identifiable because they are part of the very air
                    that both the writer and the reader have breathed through education, and the
                    experiences of being a child, of being taught to be a Christian child, or the
